br>  Posts: 90<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/21/02 10:33:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2942.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.tampalocksmith.com/holding/ExtraCrispy.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ok, here goes my questions...</span><hr size=1> The Trivial Loot Code activates when any member of a party does not (and cannot) get experience from a mob the party has killed.  Whether that member is too low (mob super red) or too high (mob green) makes no difference.  If the TLC kicks in on the mob you've killed, you will see, in red:<br>
<br>
A_Insert_mob_here_01 was a Trivial Challenge to your party!<br>
<br>
This is how you know the TLC got ya.  And whatever magic or lore item that normally would have dropped, did not.<br>
<br>
Simple really.  The way the TLC changes the game dynamics is that you must conduct certain quests before they are too easy for you, and the harder quests and some raids now have what's called a &quot;TLC Team&quot; of lower-level PC's whose job it is to specifically kill the mob from which the drop is needed.<br>
<br>
My first experience with this was in Castle Mistmoore, where I was on the TLC team.  We had 3 teams of higher season (a level on Firona Vie is usually called a &quot;season&quot; for warriors and wisdom casters, a &quot;circle&quot; for intelligence casters, and a &quot;symphony&quot; or &quot;song&quot; for Bards...but it's really up to your imagination what you want to call your levels, just as long as you can be understood and you don't use the word &quot;level&quot; which is just SO d00d. ugh.) players running &quot;air cover&quot; for the TLC team, which had its own healer, nuker, and tank team.  It worked.  We integrated well and got what we needed.<br>
<br>
It also makes the young ones more valuable to the old ones.  On other servers, once you hit the high end game, you don't have much use for &quot;newbies&quot; anymore.  On Firiona Vie, it's common practice to hire lower level people to do quests, or to assist in quests that you have become too high for.  On a positive side, the TLC promotes cooperation and the use of real people skills to get what you want.<br>
<br>
You want Jboots?  You can't just level up to 60 and camp the AC anymore...he'll TLC out and you'll never get them.  So you have to make a deal with someone younger who can still get EXP from that AC...or you must do it yourself when there is still quite an element of risk.<br>
<br>
In my opinion, the TLC brought back into line a lot of the original intents for the quests and the drops that the &quot;no drop&quot; code was intended to fix but didn't.<br>
<br>
Yes, it can be a hassle.<br>
<br>
Yes, it takes some getting used to.<br>
<br>
But it makes sure that those who are SUPPOSED to kill the proper mobs at the proper levels...do.  And pharming becomes just another dangerous way to make money...but you can still do it.<br>
<br>
Omi <p><img src=http://www.tampalocksmith.com/holding/omi3.gif>

